    std::string url = "https://development-oauth.ready.gg/?url_redirect=" + variable + "%2F&returnSecureToken=true&appId=io.getready.rgngodot&lang=ru";

    std::cout << url << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the string variable `variable` holds the value you want to replace "rgngodot://" with. The `url` variable concatenates the parts of the URL using the `+` operator, combining the parts with the `variable` value in between.

Another approach is to use C++'s string formatting capabilities using `std::sprintf` or `std::stringstream`. Here's an example using `std::sprintf`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    char variable[] = "your_variable_value";
    char url[200];

    std::sprintf(url, "https://development-oauth.ready.gg/?url_redirect=%s%%2F&returnSecureToken=true&appId=io.getready.rgngodot&lang=ru", variable);

    std::cout << url << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the `url` variable is an array of characters (C-style string). `std::sprintf` function is used to format the URL string, replacing `%s` with the value of `variable` using the `%%` to escape the `%` symbol.

