To implement a simple event delegate approach in C++, you can use function pointers or functors (function objects). Here's an example using function pointers:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

// Event delegate type definition
typedef void(*EventDelegate)(int);

// Event class
class Event {
public:
    // Event delegate
    EventDelegate delegate;

    // Trigger the event
    void TriggerEvent(int value) {
        if (delegate != nullptr) {
            delegate(value);
        }
    }
};

// Event handler function
void MyEventHandler(int value) {
    std::cout << "Event triggered with value: " << value << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    // Create an instance of the event
    Event myEvent;

    // Assign the event handler
    myEvent.delegate = MyEventHandler;

    // Trigger the event
    myEvent.TriggerEvent(42);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we define the `EventDelegate` type as a function pointer that takes an `int` parameter and returns `void`.

The `Event` class has a `delegate` member of type `EventDelegate`, which represents the event handler function to be called when the event is triggered.

The `TriggerEvent` function checks if the delegate is assigned (`delegate != nullptr`) and then calls the delegate function with the provided value.

In `main`, we create an instance of the `Event` class and assign the `MyEventHandler` function as the event handler using the `delegate` member. Finally, we trigger the event by calling `myEvent.TriggerEvent(42)`.

Note that this is a simple implementation of a delegate approach using function pointers. For more complex scenarios or additional features, you might consider using function objects or more advanced event systems provided by libraries or frameworks.

To remove a value by reference from a vector in C++, you can use the `erase-remove idiom` or the `remove_if` function from the `<algorithm>` library. Here's an example using the `erase-remove idiom`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

    // Value to remove (by reference)
    int valueToRemove = 3;

    // Find the iterator pointing to the value
    auto it = std::find(numbers.begin(), numbers.end(), valueToRemove);

    // If the value is found, erase it from the vector
    if (it != numbers.end()) {
        numbers.erase(it);
    }

    // Display the updated vector
    for (const auto& number : numbers) {
        std::cout << number << " ";
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have a vector `numbers` with some integer values. We want to remove a specific value (`valueToRemove`) from the vector by reference.

First, we use `std::find` from the `<algorithm>` library to find the iterator (`it`) pointing to the value in the vector. If the value is found (i.e., `it != numbers.end()`), we call `numbers.erase(it)` to remove it from the vector.

Finally, we display the updated vector using a range-based loop.

Note that this method removes the first occurrence of the value found. If you have multiple occurrences and want to remove all of them, you can use a loop or the `remove_if` function.

